cambridge analytica‚Äôs parent company, scl, had won contracts with the us state department and was pitching to the pentagon, and wylie was genuinely freaked out. - it‚Äôs insane, he told me one night. - the company has created psychological profiles of 230 million americans. and now they want to work with the pentagon? it‚Äôs like nixon on steroids.

text:
with times changing, and the gender bias coming over stronger than ever before with movements such as ‚Äú#metoo‚Äù and ‚Äú#timesup‚Äù and in place of talking about universal sisterhood, (a happy dream, of the bygone third phase of feminism) we have gone forth to realise that there is no fixed recipe to treat the global disaster that is sexism. feminism is a colloquial notion, changing with sexual, racial and religious backdrops. there is no one track agenda under the umbrella of feminism. as we stand at the brink of 2020, an era ending and new ones beginning extending sisterhood is not enough, saying ‚Äúwe support our women‚Äù or terms like ‚Äúequal pay for equal work‚Äù will not satisfy  those across the globe who stand for feminism: a concept that has never been about putting women on a pedestal, but has been about conquering the divide between the two genders: to see them both stand shoulder to shoulder. it‚Äôs time we realise that being a feminist means we stand up for what we believe in: fight back and not just preach like a pastor. it‚Äôs time scores were set straight, opting for fairness for both the ‚Äúfair‚Äù- and ‚Äúnot so fair‚Äù- sex.

text:
dreads (a villanelle)

a poem i wrote 3 years ago at the end of a relationship with someone i committed to locs (dreadlocks) for. he had them, too. he‚Äôs remains faithfully committed to them to this day. good for him.

every strand is loc‚Äôd for who we be
birthed from us, matted to perfection
could‚Äôve told me you didn‚Äôt love me

several months since we have not been ‚Äúwe‚Äù
didn‚Äôt say, but i had suspicion 
every strand is loc‚Äôd for who we be

thought i‚Äôd cut my hair since now i‚Äôm me
can‚Äôt believe i‚Äôm in this position
could‚Äôve told me you didn‚Äôt love me

i look at these ropes, its you i see
bound by love, pain and lost affection 
every strand is loc‚Äôd for who we be

re-define my hair and then i‚Äôm free
it‚Äôs now time to find my direction
could‚Äôve told me you didn‚Äôt love me

movin‚Äô on but i still long for thee
time to let go of my affliction
every strand is loc‚Äôd for who we be
could‚Äôve told me you didn‚Äôt love me

text:
livia, 19 tahun, jakarta. 
hello everyone. my name is livia. as a woman, i‚Äôm obviously familiar with things like ‚Äúcatcall‚Äù and other sexual harassment both verbal and non-verbal. i‚Äôm going to tell you my story about being sexually harassed by a stranger. my story may not be the worst, but note that any form of sexual harassment cannot be justified. i was out in a club with all my girl friends, having fun, dancing to the music and basically enjoying the night and all of a sudden a group of guys chose to stand right behind my crowds. we didn‚Äôt think anything of it at first, but everything changed when i felt someone‚Äôs touching my lower-back part and i spontaneously turn around just to see those guys looking compeletely normal as if nothing happened. i was furious, scared, ashamed, confused, and at that moment i just want to cry and go home. i told one of my friends and she actually stood up for me and scold them, but none of the guys admitted to do it, let alone apologize. i didn‚Äôt wear clothes that shows too much skin or anything, and yet i still get treated like that. this proves that sexual harassment happens not because what we wear, nor what we do, and it is never our fault. 
if you ever experience something like this, don‚Äôt hesitate to share your story with us and help us to fight this together! you are not alone
.
.
.

text:
bella, 20 tahun, jakarta. 
aku pernah lagi berdiri di pinggir jalan menunggu jemput untuk pulang . jalanan macet, jadi banyak kendaraan yang berhenti. lalu ada kayak abang ojek yang mangkal disitu, awalnya cuma ngelirik ke arah aku. lama-lama jadi ngomong yang aneh-aneh. ‚Äòmau ke mana neng? mau dianterin enggak? buat neng saya gratisin deh tapi minta nomor hapenya boleh enggak? cemberut aja, senyum dong biar cakep. sombong amat sih,‚Äô kayak gitu. aku diem aja dan terus pasang wajah jutek. eh dia malah makin menjadi dengan mulai berdiri dan mulai mendekat kesamping aku dan seperti mau merangkul, disitu aku bener- bener merasa makin takut dan akhirnya aku pun langsung jalan,pergi menjauh dari tempat itu .
.
.
#keepyourhandstoyourself #handsoffproject #againstsexualharassment #metoo #metoomovement #speakup
name: HANDSOFF. PROJECT

text: cyntoia brown has been granted clemency!!! she will be released on parole on august 7th! if you know this young woman‚Äôs story then you know what amazing this news is! at 16 years old she was a victim of child sex-trafficking at the hands of her older, abusive, pimp boyfriend who went by the nickname ‚Äúcut throat‚Äù. in august of 2004 (when she was only 16!!!)she shot and killed a 43 year old man who had picked her up to pay her for sex when she believed he was about to shoot her. in 2006 she was sentenced to life in prison. having served 15 years and totally turned her life around (although i see her as a victim in this case and not somebody who was a career criminal in need of rehabilitation) yesterday it was announced that the governor of tennessee has granted her clemency! this young lady will finally have a chance to live a normal life and plans to use her own experience to help the youth that are growing up the way she did. her mess is now her message and i cannot wait to see all the amazing things this woman will do! #cyntoiabrown #metoo #endchildsextrafficing #justiceforcyntoiabrown

viola, 20 tahun, depok. 
halo! gue, viola monica. disini gue mau ngebagi cerita gue yang kurang ngeenakin nih, jadi waktu itu gue lagi ngantri salah satu bubble tea gitukan. terus karna antriannya ini panjang banget, plus penuh sama salah satu ojek online soalnya ada promo gitukan. nah gue antrinya agak keluar dari barisan. karna terlalu mepet antara depan dan belakang. tapi, entah kenapa gue udah kasih jarak kaya gitu, yang menurut gue kayanya gamungkin deh kalo ‚Äúgaksengaja‚Äù kesentuh gitu. tapi kaget bgt sih bagian belakang gue disentuh gitu. karna seperti yang gue bilang, dengan jarak segitu gamungkin kan bagian tubuh belakang gue bisa dia kenain gitu... mau negor juga gue takut disangka gr, tapi kesel banget, kaget juga sih. cuma bisa pasrah aja tapiüò£
dan gue juga pernah. lagi berdiri dipinggir jalan sama temen - temen gue. tapi entah kenapa tiba-tiba tangan gue ditarik sama bapak2 lagi!!! shock banget sih. gangerti maksudnya apa. pas gue ngeliatin dia, dia diem. tapi gue juga diem karna sangking shocknya gangerti maksud dia apaüò•üò≠ abis itu gue nyesel kenapa cuma diem ga negor tuh bapak2üò°üò≠

text:
okay ladies i‚Äôm about to m on a rant:

we have fought to have body shaming recognized, #metoo, bullying and equality and yet woman bashing woman is so common we just fluff past it. 
well stop üõë it!!! today in the grocery store there was a beautiful younger woman shopping (just shopping), when 2 women started to make comments loud enough that the beautiful woman would hear and others in the area...‚Äùdoesn‚Äôt she think she‚Äôs all that‚Äù...‚Äùhow much did that face cost‚Äù...‚Äùshe‚Äôs lucky to look like that because obviously that‚Äôs all she has‚Äù...‚Äù i wonder what she charges‚Äù and several other statements.

of course this hurt the woman...you could see it on her face as the other woman laughed and moved on. i approached her and asked if she was ok...her reply was all to familiar ‚Äúyeah you get used to it‚Äù omg seriously how can one get used to that. i told her she was a stunning lady and to hold her head high and shine and never allow others insecurities or jealousy to steal her thunder.

i walked out remembering how just a few weeks earlier at my pop up event a group of women had done the same thing to me. they intentionally were cruel, hurtful and bullied me with the intention of humiliating me. i was hurt and degraded all because it made them feel better about who they were. i remembered saying that evening ‚Äúyeah it hurts like crazy but you get used to it‚Äù

bullshit!!! you don‚Äôt get used to it!!! no one gets used to it and nor should they. like this woman today i walked away holding my head high not allowing them to see me cry. i‚Äôm sure i will face this again and i pray i have the strength to carry myself with the same dignity i was raised to have.

my point of this is to say ladies how can we demand respect, kindness and understanding from others when just because another women feels like a threat to our egos we bash her. so please before you jump to conclusions or form an opinion on nothing more than appearance stop üõë and ask if you would want someone to do that to you!!! sorry gang this one just hit home today and no one deserves to be treated that way!!! #bullying #meangirls #jealous #stopit #meanwomen #buildup #buildup #stopthehate #betheexample #riseabove #stophatred

text:
i was going through old pictures the other day and i was honestly surprised at the emotion that came over me. as i looked at them, my heart ached because i remember that girl...and i wish that i could go back, hug her, and tell her that one day everything would be ok. but honestly, i don‚Äôt think i‚Äôd believe me even if i did.
...
the girl on the top right was 15 or 16 years old and was hurting so deeply that even she didn‚Äôt understand it. she held a secret that was poisoning her from the inside out and she used food for comfort. that food turned to weight gain and that weight took her already low confidence and made it even lower. she hated herself, everything about her. she felt like she was unlovable and couldn‚Äôt see herself ever being truly happy. and the man that took the picture, the one man in this world she should‚Äôve been able to trust more than anyone, was still taking every opportunity he could to hurt her. she often thought about dying but she felt an obligation to be there for her mom and little sister. so she kept going, pushing herself to be ‚Äúsuccessful‚Äù in the hopes that one day she would be worthy of real love.
...
the girl on the bottom right was 20 years old and had just graduated college. it should‚Äôve been one of the happiest times in her life but it was one of the lowest. she was tired and scared and desperate for anything that would make her feel anything but the way she was feeling. she used drinking and sometimes drugs to numb her pain and she was so desperate for love that she couldn‚Äôt even see the love that was right in front of her. some days she would do nothing but cry. she couldn‚Äôt sleep but she couldn‚Äôt get out of bed. she was always sick and she was still holding on to a horrible secret that was literally killing her. she made so many mistakes in the pursuit of happiness because she didn‚Äôt know what happiness really was. and one year after this picture was taken...she tried to take her life.
...

i was going through old pictures the other day and i was honestly surprised at the emotion that came over me. as i looked at them, my heart ached because i remember that girl...and i wish that i could go back, hug her, and tell her that one day everything would be ok. but honestly, i don‚Äôt think i‚Äôd believe me even if i did.
...
the girl on the top right was 15 or 16 years old and was hurting so deeply that even she didn‚Äôt understand it. she held a secret that was poisoning her from the inside out and she used food for comfort. that food turned to weight gain and that weight took her already low confidence and made it even lower. she hated herself, everything about her. she felt like she was unlovable and couldn‚Äôt see herself ever being truly happy. and the man that took the picture, the one man in this world she should‚Äôve been able to trust more than anyone, was still taking every opportunity he could to hurt her. she often thought about dying but she felt an obligation to be there for her mom and little sister. so she kept going, pushing herself to be ‚Äúsuccessful‚Äù in the hopes that one day she would be worthy of real love.
...
the girl on the bottom right was 20 years old and had just graduated college. it should‚Äôve been one of the happiest times in her life but it was one of the lowest. she was tired and scared and desperate for anything that would make her feel anything but the way she was feeling. she used drinking and sometimes drugs to numb her pain and she was so desperate for love that she couldn‚Äôt even see the love that was right in front of her. some days she would do nothing but cry. she couldn‚Äôt sleep but she couldn‚Äôt get out of bed. she was always sick and she was still holding on to a horrible secret that was literally killing her. she made so many mistakes in the pursuit of happiness because she didn‚Äôt know what happiness really was. and one year after this picture was taken...she tried to take her life.
...
*continued in comments*

text:

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
sally‚Äôs had it with being dismissed, disrespected, being talked down to, blamed and being treated less than equal...less than human. 
sally is #woke. 
48‚Äùx48‚Äù

ink/paint/canvas

sally wakes up with the #metoo movement and has had enough of staying silent....about anything. 
hear her roar. 
a mere part of a larger series of artworks that were to be, and are, my commentary on where it seems our country, society and culture is today compared to when i was a child. 
the crux of the series is based on childhood cartoons and characters that i had grown up with and that represent my childhood. now, these characters are distorted into something that will never, at least unlikely, be the same again. they used to be sharp, clean lines and brightly colored.... now they are rough, dirty, twisted and in black and white. 
the peanuts gang were holiday staple cartoons as a child.

i hope you like it. i‚Äôm trying to figure the new world i live and where the old one has gone.

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

text: 2018 you were a whirlwind. dear ones departed by death or heartbreak. it‚Äôs not the same without you aunt chrissy, aretha...oh! my heart!. you burned down cities, washed some away. evil kicked up dust and love refused defeat. we can still win this. i trusted dangerous people. magic was real. pay attention. i thought i only spoke english but foreign languages become familiar when souls connected.  amazed but not surprised. caro...i understood every word. i was imam for a day. my family grew. i lost my sistar. boys were boys in the worst way. 13 years and i still miss you the same. i‚Äôm surviving i guess. yeah, #metoo . i‚Äôm inspired by my own sense of romance. but the sign says it‚Äôs really not me it‚Äôs you. land a few gigs. love helps more, but money helps. nothing feels easy. adventures i travel for. it feels good at first. my world got bigger and smaller, too. mystical things still fascinate me. veils are lifted. your hand holds tight to mine. i can even fall asleep crossing the street. habibi, is it finally you? i dream wildly and chase some. i learn a new pain. people are so foolish sometimes and so am i. i feel precious and also worthless at moments. my son falls in love for the 1st time. wisdom feels burdensome when i am only planting seeds for now.or so it seems. i grew up yet sometimes i was my old self. more times i was new. sometimes i forgot myself. i was such a woman. i was such a girl. i took chances. human forms usurp human beings. i felt lost. still..i can‚Äôt seem to get my rose colored glasses off. maybe i never wanted to. in the seas i was found. swimming? drowning?  oh...love. maybe a bit of both. i let go of things that have needed discarding. but, i hold on to your rope tighter still. ahh....love. it was very good year‚ú®üíõ‚ú® #alhamdullilahforeverything

text:
protests erupted tuesday outside the west hollywood home of prominent democratic donor ed buck, with activists calling for buck's arrest after a man was found dead in the apartment early monday -- 17 months after a deceased male escort was discovered there. neighbors of buck's, who were drawn out of their homes as a result of the protest, said they have the same questions as everyone else and have made their own calls to police, buck, a well-known figure in lgbt political circles, has given more than $500,000 to a range of democratic groups and candidates ‚Äî including former president barack obama, former secretary of state hillary clinton and los angeles mayor eric garcetti.
in july of last year, prosecutors declined to file charges against buck in the death of moore. according to a coroner's report, buck's apartment was full of drug paraphernalia, including 24 syringes containing brown residue, five glass pipes with white residue and burn marks, a plastic straw with possible white residue, clear plastic bags with white powdery residue and a clear plastic bag containing a piece of crystal-like substance. #breakingnews #edbuck #viral #hilaryclinton #donaldtrump #georgebush #usa #melaniatrump #michelleobama #trump #president #methaddict #barackobama #meme #blm #georgehwbush #rapevictim #bush41 #funeral #nationaldayofmourning #democrats #georgewbush #metoo #mrstealyourgirl #restinpeace #lgbt #survivingrkelly #riskitall #theshaderoom

text:
this 6 part documentary has been overwhelming to watch, and i would urge anyone and everyone to watch. .
.

i can never listen to his music again after watching this, especially hearing where some of the songs originated from and are inspired from. .
.
absolutely heart breaking hearing what these young women had to go through especially the fact that these are our sisters/ our black women.  and even more breaking to hear some are still imprisoned by the predator.
.
.
. 
it is overwhelming and it is absurd that he is still free to roam and carry on his life whilst destroying everyone and everything in his path. .
.
.
faith has taught me to see the miraculous in everyday life: the miracle of ordinary black women resisting and rising about evil forces in society, where forces work to destroy and subvert the creative power and energy god gave black women.

text: "i'll make you a star!" this was one of the many lies some of kelly's victims were told to lure them in. young impressionable teens in search of their big break and they believed a man who was already famous and succeeding in the industry was going to help them. it's a classic form of grooming and manipulation. and look at the precision of his manipulative tendencies, he actually took the girls to the studio and allowed them proximity to their dream so it actually felt within reach. as a result, they quickly developed trust so when boundaries were crossed, they didn't know how to advocate for themselves and they were afraid to rebuff him. there were even parents who bought into the lie thinking they could control the situation, but a predator always plays their game on their terms. don't ever think you can gain an advantage with them because this is all they think about, and their depravity knows no limits so you can't ever know what they're thinking and the lengths they'll go to for self gratification. this is true for the coaches, tutors, priests, pastors, camp counselors and every other professional who uses fulfilling a dream or a need to sexually abuse kids. #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #family @officialmuterkelly

text:
looks like the #metoo movement is rapidly approaching hip-hop. grown men preying on children seems to be rampant. i just dont get it. if you're 18...hell if you're 21... i dont even see you. and if i do its certainly not from a sexual standpoint. 
as a male, the idea anyone could, "get off," to adolescent behavior -no matter how "mature," they appear, or force yourself on another who has no interest in you because their in need of a #job or #opportunity is not only disgusting but its lame af. 
while some can call me many things, illegal and immoral sexual predatory behavior would never be some of em. 
if #you dont want me i dont want you. and as a grown ass man "experience" (in all areas -if you catch my drift üòà) rises to the top as an important and non-negotiable quality one must have to get the green light. 
the idea one suddenly becomes an object of interest to claimed by means of force or mental manipulation is very off putting and only echoes your weak "game" ability. let me be clear: if you're in a position of #power and you use that power to manipulate and force someone into dropping their undergarments so you can bask in their body fluids (eww what a visual) you are the lamest nigga on #earth!!!! from hearing about the vast age differences between diddy and misa (is that how you spell her name), dame and aaliyah, jay and bey, and r. kelly and an entire high school, apparently, theres an epidemic out there i wasnt aware of. from radio personalities, to producers, the allegations, i'm sure only skim the surface. 
when i think about all the false allegations thrown on #queer #people, that still gets said today--just in more private, smaller #circles where #homophobia is very much still a more natural way of #life-- that we're sexual deviants who tear at the fabric of our blah, blah, blah, it's very upsetting. maybe that's the wrong word... i think disappointing is prolly more accurate.

thank god i dont have #children, yo. how can you be a sane parent in today's time?? seriously! ....brings a whole new meaning to, "women and children first," dont it.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

üá¨üáßÔ∏è
#mollywood has been under fire for reinforcing gender stereotypes, typically through scenes in which the hero tames or puts the woman in her place. thanks to cultural movements like #metoo and women in cinema collective (#wcc), now there is a clear rethink in the industry about masculine triumph becoming the logical conclusion or moral of the story. a slew of recent movies like the one referred to above have strived to portray a new kind of masculinity taking into account post feministic sensibilities. in fact, just the way hyper masculinity was deployed earlier to get applause, the concept of women empowerment is now being put to formulaic use in a bid to win plaudits. üá∑üá∫Ô∏è

mgtow 101: networking/ strolling the room

it's like wanting to approach the hottest woman at the club, who is in a group of 5. some men will go right for her (which isn't wrong) and some men will go for her friends and pay her the least attention. it's the psychology of the approach. if she sees the uglier girls getting more attention than her, it makes her think wait what's going on. women are extremely petty this way. men have egos that are just as high, thus making them just as petty.

now this isn't a strategy to use in business situations when you have to be aggressive to make sales or build your brand. when you are trying to grow your brand, you must go out and aggressively  get the customers.

this is more so for a situation where you are at and event looking to gain knowledge and contacts with little pressure. let's say you are at a fundraiser on the behalf of a friend, so you don't have much pressure or incentive to go out there and sell yourself, yet you still want to put yourself in the right circle.

this is an example of two ways to go about it. it's more so a mindset to have more than a way to move. when you have an abundance mindset and a mindset of you being the price you move differently. when you understand psychology you will also move differently.

so don't take this as gold and use it as an excuse not to hustle a room as hard as the next man but keep it in mind for light events, club scenes and entertainment nights.

text:
@globeandmail news has sparked quite the discussion with their recent article: educating grayson: are inclusive classrooms failing students?
.
this article talks about a 7-year-old boy named grayson who was recently diagnosed with autism and was expelled from school for striking and educational assistant and giving her a concussion. his mother received calls daily about his behaviour and his struggles of being in a "regular" classroom.
.
.
this topic is very dear to my heart. working with one of the largest school boards in canada for the last 15 years i have seen and been involved in a lot of situations similar to this one, but you may be very surprised about my views on inclusion and education.
.
.
join me thursday live @ 9pm est.  i will be talking about inclusive education, what it really is, and my personal opinion of whether or not it really works.  i would love to know your thoughts as well. should kids with complex needs be in a regular classroom or in a "special" class to address their special needs? do you have a story about your child being excluded or maybe your child was a victim of another student with complex needs? comment below and be sure to join me on thursday. .
.
.

simple example: in a group of friends, you see that someone is bullying/ taunting the other one, coming from an oppressed caste on their language, clothing, reservation, for not knowing pop-culture shows, or anything‚Äî you choose to stay silent and laugh along with others, then you're equally an obnoxious casteist asshole. 
second example: you know that specific person had a history of being casteist and many people from oppressed castes call them out, but you still choose to encourage/worship/follow them ‚Äî you can't be a supporter of anti-caste movement in any manner as you're complicit af and is equally casteist for ignoring the resistance of bahujans around you.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

1. 2018 and prior years saw vibrators and similar products improve in quality and gain traction with mainstream retailers as ‚Äòwellness/ beauty product‚Äô. this saw vibrators and similar products gain mainstream acceptance. 2019 is therefore set to see this trend continue with many more mainstream retailers jumping on this bandwagon.
2. many positive trends from 2018 are also bound to continue. on the home front, there is a general cultural willingness to discuss sexual abuse/rape. 2019 therefore is likely to see this progressive attitude continue with more awareness been raised and fewer cases been swept under the carpet. 
3. still on the home front, in a country where sex is still considered a taboo, younger people in particular feel more open talking about their sexual and reproductive health thanks to innovations such as @mypaddi_ng. first of its kind in #nigeria, mypaddi grew in popularity in 2018, and is likely to become even more popular in 2019 as more people find this a useful resource.
4. asides from promoting conversations around accountability and consent, the #metoo movement saw attitudes shift around sex. this change is set to affect everyday relationships in the bedroom. 2019 may see female pleasure starting to take more of a centre stage, as women like never before are speaking up more and prioritising their #pleasure. 
5. as well as new female sex toys been introduced in 2019, the new year is set to see male sex toys become more popular as the stigma around them continues to fade. (but that‚Äôs not all when it comes to men), 2019 is also set to see more men embrace adult sex education, in particular embracing the art of female orgasms. (now that‚Äôs a change we‚Äôve all been waiting for!).
6. in the world of sex tech, 2019 will see #apple launch an intimacy remote app with luxury sex toy company ohmibod as many couples continue to look for innovative ways to make their sex lives flourish.

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
under the spirit of #metoo, we highlighted the case of sexual violence that is still prevalent in today's society, particularly towards girls and women. with that in mind, almost unanimously, we understood the importance of consent in sexual activities
.
.
it is timely that now we have an open discussion about what consent is and more importantly, what it is not. surely, it is not a justification for rape. let's discuss further in our event below:

topic: beyond consent
date: saturday, 12 january 2019
venue: kenobi space, gedung colony kemang, lt. 6
movie: fat girl (2001)
schedule:
18.30 - 18.45: teaser of "invisible hopes" and q & a with director tiar simorangkir @boruakkir
18.45 - 20.15: movie screening
20.15 - 21.45: discussion with vivi widyawati (perempuan mahardhika) and anastasia sijabat (jakarta cinema club)

ticket: 30k

warning: the film is rated r and includes some rape and gore scenes.

discussion will be held in bahasa indonesia.

online ticket can be purchased at livelife:
http://bit.ly/sf120119
name: Jakarta Cinema Club

text:
‚Äúthe storm is coming,‚Äù say the conspiracy theorizers whose grotesque imaginings terrified the country to attention this week. maybe they‚Äôre right.

the simplest description of the plot line goes something like this: president trump isn‚Äôt under investigation; he is only pretending to be, as part of a countercoup to restore power to the people after more than a century of governmental control by a globalist cabal. also, there are pedophiles.

a figure named ‚Äúq,‚Äù who supposedly possesses q-level security clearance, disperses ‚Äúcrumbs‚Äù that ‚Äúbakers‚Äù bring together to create a ‚Äúdough‚Äù of synthesized information. (this is not how baking works, but that seems the least of our worries.) because q is the 17th letter in the alphabet and 17 is also a number trump has said a few times, among other clearly-not-coincidences, he is the real deal, not an internet troll engaged in an elaborate example of live-action role-play.

that‚Äôs what qanon followers really want, after all. that‚Äôs where their ‚Äústorm‚Äù motto comes from. most americans were puzzled when, in a meeting with military leaders months ago, trump said, ‚Äúyou know what this represents? maybe it‚Äôs the calm before the storm.‚Äù but these theorists thought they knew exactly what he was talking about. trump was pointing at the officers‚Äô uniforms.

the storm qanon truthers predict will never strike because the conspiracy that obsesses them doesn‚Äôt exist. but while they wait for it, they‚Äôll try to whip up the winds, and the rest of us will struggle to find shelter. qanon is scary because it‚Äôs getting bigger, it‚Äôs scary because we don‚Äôt know how to stop it, and it‚Äôs scary because the people behind it won‚Äôt be stopped, and, until their illusory storm arrives, they won‚Äôt be satisfied.

‚Äúthe storm is coming,‚Äù say the conspiracy theorizers whose grotesque imaginings terrified the country to attention this week. maybe they‚Äôre right.

the simplest description of the plot line goes something like this: president trump isn‚Äôt under investigation; he is only pretending to be, as part of a countercoup to restore power to the people after more than a century of governmental control by a globalist cabal. also, there are pedophiles.

a figure named ‚Äúq,‚Äù who supposedly possesses q-level security clearance, disperses ‚Äúcrumbs‚Äù that ‚Äúbakers‚Äù bring together to create a ‚Äúdough‚Äù of synthesized information. (this is not how baking works, but that seems the least of our worries.) because q is the 17th letter in the alphabet and 17 is also a number trump has said a few times, among other clearly-not-coincidences, he is the real deal, not an internet troll engaged in an elaborate example of live-action role-play.

that‚Äôs what qanon followers really want, after all. that‚Äôs where their ‚Äústorm‚Äù motto comes from. most americans were puzzled when, in a meeting with military leaders months ago, trump said, ‚Äúyou know what this represents? maybe it‚Äôs the calm before the storm.‚Äù but these theorists thought they knew exactly what he was talking about. trump was pointing at the officers‚Äô uniforms.

the storm qanon truthers predict will never strike because the conspiracy that obsesses them doesn‚Äôt exist. but while they wait for it, they‚Äôll try to whip up the winds, and the rest of us will struggle to find shelter. qanon is scary because it‚Äôs getting bigger, it‚Äôs scary because we don‚Äôt know how to stop it, and it‚Äôs scary because the people behind it won‚Äôt be stopped, and, until their illusory storm arrives, they won‚Äôt be satisfied.

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
‚Äúthe storm is coming,‚Äù say the conspiracy theorizers whose grotesque imaginings terrified the country to attention this week. maybe they‚Äôre right.

the simplest description of the plot line goes something like this: president trump isn‚Äôt under investigation; he is only pretending to be, as part of a countercoup to restore power to the people after more than a century of governmental control by a globalist cabal. also, there are pedophiles.

a figure named ‚Äúq,‚Äù who supposedly possesses q-level security clearance, disperses ‚Äúcrumbs‚Äù that ‚Äúbakers‚Äù bring together to create a ‚Äúdough‚Äù of synthesized information. (this is not how baking works, but that seems the least of our worries.) because q is the 17th letter in the alphabet and 17 is also a number trump has said a few times, among other clearly-not-coincidences, he is the real deal, not an internet troll engaged in an elaborate example of live-action role-play.

that‚Äôs what qanon followers really want, after all. that‚Äôs where their ‚Äústorm‚Äù motto comes from. most americans were puzzled when, in a meeting with military leaders months ago, trump said, ‚Äúyou know what this represents? maybe it‚Äôs the calm before the storm.‚Äù but these theorists thought they knew exactly what he was talking about. trump was pointing at the officers‚Äô uniforms.

the storm qanon truthers predict will never strike because the conspiracy that obsesses them doesn‚Äôt exist. but while they wait for it, they‚Äôll try to whip up the winds, and the rest of us will struggle to find shelter. qanon is scary because it‚Äôs getting bigger, it‚Äôs scary because we don‚Äôt know how to stop it, and it‚Äôs scary because the people behind it won‚Äôt be stopped, and, until their illusory storm arrives, they won‚Äôt be satisfied.

molly roberts
the washington post

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text: honestly, the last post that i made about #metoo i didn‚Äôt say much but on my page i‚Äôll be talking about my personal experience with speaking out because i know there‚Äôs a lot of people out there, not just girls who‚Äôve been been through this & i want everyone to know it‚Äôs okay to talk about it. whenever you do though , whenever you speak out some people will question you and some whom you don‚Äôt even know will take your word and help you through every step of the process. there will be days that you won‚Äôt want to speak no more and repeat your story for the millionth time to the millionth person you are seeing. no matter how annoyed you are of saying the same thing over & over again don‚Äôt lose hope. everyone has a different experience with it. (october 3, 2017) is significant to me because i broke my silence on being abused for 12 years of my life basically as of rn all my life is what it felt like. from age 4-16. my mom confronted my abuser once she found out herself when she asked me privately if i had been abused by my abuser . i simply didn‚Äôt answer , i broke down in tears . my mom knew, i had indeed been abused by this person she had put all of her trust in since i was a young child. my mom was in disbelief, anger ran through her mind and body . she confronts him, & he acts surprised because he was caught off guard, he proceeds to deny it . as i walk in & i hear him deny , my silence is broken. i yell at the top of my lungs ‚Äúwhy are you lying? she knows the truth . why would i be making this up? im tired of being quite and being abused by you‚Äù i‚Äôve never ever yelled so loud in my life before . i‚Äôm pretty sure my neighbors found out since our walls are very thin & i live in an apartment complex. time passes by my mom attacks him with all her force, starts beating him to the point he had scratched him & he was bleeding. i was scared i didn‚Äôt know what my mom would do next out of anger towards my abuser. i try to stop her because my younger brothers are witnessing mommy beat up daddy. (not my dad) they become very worried and i try calming them down because they‚Äôre crying , my moms crying on the floor , & my abuser and i are going back and forth about my mothers

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
footage of nigel farage swigging a pint and thanking steve bannon and breitbart for the brexit result was deleted from a breitbart youtube channel, following the data scandal surrounding cambridge analytica. - well done bannon, well done breitbart, the ex-ukip leader announces in the short clip. - you helped with this. hugely.

farage‚Äôs nod to steve bannon certainly hasn‚Äôt aged well in the context of the recent storm around cambridge analytica‚Äôs influence over the eu referendum.

it was revealed that data from 50 million facebook profiles were looked at against the electoral register, and then used to build an algorithm which analyses people‚Äôs personality traits in relation to their voting behaviour.

this data could then be used to find potential swing voters and create messages tailored to influence them politically.

the firm‚Äôs vice president at the time was steve bannon, who was also head of the right-wing website breitbart and was running donald trump‚Äôs campaign to become us president.

anna o'donohue
inews

text:
i have refrained from commenting on the sexual harassment and rape allegations at bfm because i wanted to allow the investigation to run its course. 
after the anonymous email containing these allegations surfaced, the station hired independent investigators who created an anonymous channel through which people were able to report and give evidence in whatever manner they were comfortable. this support and privacy was what encouraged and enabled many to come forward to speak up, and these mechanisms are necessary in the course of handling such issues. 
in my experience of reporting a case of sexual harassment in the past, i was not offered this kind of support. in fact, i went to an ngo and reached out to many members of civil society for help, but my complaint was not taken seriously to say the least. i think it was because i raised a complaint against a fellow member of the ngo community. 
i have spoken about this experience in public, and the case eventually ended up being investigated independently by the ngo's funders. they were ordered to return the funds and issue an apology to me. the ngo has since ceased operations; but to this day, i have not received my apology, nor have they made any public acknowledgment of the incident. recalling that experience today, the frustration i feel is as strong as it was the first time i spoke about it. so i know how lonely it can feel to be an activist experiencing a violation of my rights, while my fellow activists refuse to stand up for me. (continued in comments)

#tradition is so important to me and i cherish the traditions i have over the #holidays with my daughter on our annual attendance of the rose_parade üåπthat i feel privileged to live near and able to #celebrate new beginnings at each year. to me 1Ô∏è‚É£ word describes my #goal in life as 2019 begins:  #impact  by that i mean as a #parent first and second by the the #philanthropic work i do with charitable organizations to make a positive impact in the lives of others. i will continue my legal work advocating for children abused and bullied, #survivors of the las vegas mass shooting, & #metoo cases involving sexual harassment & racial discrimination. 
as i thought my life was ending in the #lasvegasshooting i thought of what kind of imprint i had made on the world thus far.  now i live my life with more #urgency to make a #difference in the lives of others. trying to take focus off of me and giving my efforts and wisdom of life‚Äôs twists and turns to others.  i am realizing that the tragedy and darker moments in my life are set ups for me to impact others and not be afraid of carving out my own #pathofdreams instead of spectating.
i am starting 2019 working on two projects to #followmydreams ‚ú®
a little teaser on the two projects:  i am pitching the idea of a weekly #talkshow and working on an immersive #artgallery based concept and adjacent #bar #restaurant that i will be launching with two business partners in the heart of #sanantonio spring/summer 2019 that will bring much joy to the #texas #community & 32 million plus annual tourists by creating a #familyfriendly experience.
more exciting news to come! üíØüçæüë®‚Äçüëßüéä

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
2018 has been heralded the year of the woman ‚Äì and what a year it was.
this year also marked the one-year anniversary of the #metoo movement, and while uk businesses, charities and politics continue to be hit by scandal and allegations of misconduct, the latter part of 2018 has seen a shift from outrage to action.
it was announced recently that the government is to introduce a code of practice to tackle workplace sexual harassment and compulsory gender pay gap reporting in april saw businesses across the country held to account for the value they place on female employees. but greater than this, women are themselves more engaged and challenging their place in society, the home and the workplace. the dialogue for change has begun; eyes have been opened, questions are being asked and answers demanded.  #gurls #workplace #woman #entrepreneur #femaleentrepreneur

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

that‚Äôs what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him ‚Äúwe can take it.‚Äù no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but it‚Äôs a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then it‚Äôs easy to come along for the ride. there‚Äôs no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. they‚Äôre both just characters on the television.

that‚Äôs what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. it‚Äôs not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. it‚Äôs that we‚Äôve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium
